We see there are some cleaning should be done before we can use these datasets:
1. Take care of the missing value in coach_salaries
2. Change the column names in coach_record
3. For consistency, change salary-related variable types to double in coach_salary and coach_record.
4. Separate variables if needed.

2.1.1. missing values

Delete some unreasonable and missing values.

# replicate the original model for cleaning

There were few positions in player_salary are the same, merge them as needed: (1) 3-4-defensive-end and 4-3-denfensive-end
(2) 3-4-denfensive-tackle and 4-3-defensive-tackle (both belong to defensive-line)
(3) linebacker, traditional-linebacker, and insider-linebacker

cornerback and safty belong to defensive-back
center belong to offensive-line
3-4-denfensive-tackle and 4-3-defensive-tackle (both belong to defensive-line)

player_salary_[player_salary_$position=='3-4-defensive-end','position'] <- '4-3-defensive-end'

player_salary_[player_salary_$position=='3-4-outside-linebacker','position'] <- '4-3-outside-linebacker'

2 What are the variables related to high salary of players?

We discuss the how total_value varies in the part 1, now we are interested in how the player are paid year by year, which is avg_year so they have such huge accumulative tptal_value. We propose the following:

2.1 position

Position is the most intuitively reason we would associate with income there are positions more important in a game, they are supposed to make more money.

2.1.1 Average highest

I take the average over the annual salary after grouping them by position.

# unique(player_salary$position)#24 positions in the data

# Select columns of position, avg_year, player to find positions with the highest salary

position_sub<- player_salary[c('position','avg_year')]%>%
  group_by(position)

p <- position_sub %>%
      summarize_each(funs(mean)) %>%
      arrange(desc(avg_year)) %>%
      head(10) %>%
      select(position) %>%
      inner_join(position_sub, by='position') %>% 
      group_by(position) %>%
      ggplot(aes(x=position, y=avg_year))+
      geom_boxplot(aes(fill=avg_year)) +
      theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90, hjust = 1))
p + stat_summary(fun=mean, color='darkred', geom='point') #red dot identifies the mean value

If we look at the number of positions by unique(), we see there are 24 positions, but we are concentrating on the highest ones, so I keep the top 10 average salary positions to display in the plot. Red dot in the plot identifies the average value.
Though the boxes are scaled by large value outliers, we cannot remove those outliers, because they represent the extraordinarily high paid players in each position, well take care of them later, Now I will zoom in to show the tendency, of these average values.

p + stat_summary(fun=mean, color='darkred', geom='point') +
    coord_trans(x = "identity", y = "identity", xlim = NULL, ylim = c(0,6e+6))

If we look at this zoomed in plot, we find the avarage annual salary of quarterback is getting close to 6 million, which could be twice of the number of 4-3 outside linebacker, but there are still 14 positions not showed here, so quarterback is indeed a highly-paid position.

If we take a closer look at the boxplot, we find all the medians are close to the bottom of the box and much lower than the red dots, which means high-paid players extensively raise the mean value, so we would like to look at those extraordinarily high paid players, i.e.the outliers mentioned before.

2.1.2 Top highest in each position

Here we extract top 10 highest paid players in top 10 high-paid positions, and plot the average annual salary versus position,

top_10_each_position <- position_sub %>%
                          summarize_each(funs(mean)) %>%
                          arrange(desc(avg_year)) %>%
                          head(10) %>%
                          select(position) %>%
                          inner_join(position_sub, by='position') %>% 
                          group_by(position) %>%
                          slice_max(order_by = avg_year, n = 10)

ggplot(top_10_each_position, aes(x=position, y=avg_year))+
      geom_boxplot() +
      theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90, hjust = 1))

This plots shows that even in the most-paid subset, quarterback has the obvious highest yearly pay. If we look at the overall trend of each position, they follow a similar trend we had in the previous box plot.

2.2 age

Another factor matters to salary could be age. It is conceivable that a player at younger age tend to be more energetic and active while older players are more experience at team-work and techniques, so there could be an optimum age preferred by clubs and willing to pay more.

2.2.1 Top player age distribution

To look at if age affect salary, we will first look at the most paid players in each position to see their age distribution.

player_salary %>% group_by(position) %>% slice_max(order_by = avg_year, n = 10) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=age)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 2,
                 color='black',
                 fill='white')+
   geom_density() +
   geom_density(alpha=.2, fill='#FF6666')+
   geom_vline(aes(xintercept=mean(age, na.rm=T)),
               color="red", linetype="dashed", size=1) #red dash is the mean

This plot has bin width of 2, and the red dashed line marks the mean of the distribution. We found most top-paid players have age between 25 and 31, and the mean is 29, very few of them are over 40, so this distribution is slightly right-skewed.

2.2.1 All players age distribution

We also interested in age distribution of all players, so we plot this:

player_salary %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=age)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 2,
                 color='black',
                 fill='white')+
   # geom_density(alpha=.2, fill="#FF6666")+
   geom_vline(aes(xintercept=mean(age, na.rm=T)),
               color="red", linetype="dashed", size=1)

The overall age distribution has a similar tendency to the top-paid one: right tail, but much heavy this time. This reflects that younger players are preferred in this game. Another evidence verifies younger preference is the mean, in this plot, the mean decreases to 26, which was 19 in the previous plot. This young-age preference is understandable, because aging and experience dont guarantee for good performance.

2.3 team

Just like some companies are willing to pay more to their employees, annual salary can vary by teams.

2.3.1 Average salary versus team

5. What are the 20 MVP players based on their earns?

The list below presents the 20 MVP, which stand for the 20 Most Valuable Players from the NFL league. For that calculation, we considered values from the dataset such as average per year (avg_year), total_guaranteed, and fully_guaranteed. As we can see, most of the players positions on this list are a quarterback. The top three were Matt Ryan (Falcons), Russel Wilson (Seahawks), and Aaron Rodgers (Packers).

# Creating column with MVP value 
df_MVP <- player_salary %>% 
  rowwise() %>%

6. What teams have the highest fully guaranteed expenses?

The graph below shows the teams with higher fully guaranteed expenses, which is the money that the teams will spend with players regardless of what happens (injury, suspension, etc.). The data was different from expected because neither of the teams that won the Super Bowl in the last three years (New England Patriots, KC Chiefs, and Tampa Bays) has more expenses due to higher investments. Therefore, more analysis is needed for different assumptions.In this case, the Bears team has the highest fully guaranteed expenses (~4,2 M dollars), followed by Red Skins (~4,1 M dollars) and Browns (~3,8 M dollars).

# Grouping by teams
library(dplyr)
df_fully <- player_salary %>% group_by(team) %>% dplyr::summarize(fully_guaranteed_mean=(mean(fully_guaranteed)))

ggplot(player_salary, aes(x= reorder(team, +fully_guaranteed), y=fully_guaranteed, color= team, fill= team)) +
    geom_col() +
    labs(x = "Team", y= "Fully guaranteed expenses ($)") + 
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  ggtitle("Teams with highest fully guaranteed expenses") +

7. What is the relationship between coach salaries and their records?

Finally, the graph below shows some relationship between coach records wins and their salaries, where we were trying to find a trend on that. We hypothesize that the percentage of wins per number of games from these coaches is highly related to how much money they make. However, as we can see in the graph, we have no clear trend on this relationship. If we dont consider an outlier, the coach salaries ranged from 2.5 million to 10 million. Maybe after 60% of wins, some coaches are showing an annual salary above 7.5 million. The coach that is making more money in the league is Andy Reid from KC Chiefs, which makes sense because he was in the last two Super Bowls and won one of them. Other than that, we would have to analyze more data to make some conclusions, maybe even looking at the number of losses, championships, etc.
